        {
          "type": "note",
          "id": "9TUvx",
          "x": 1897,
          "y": 120,
          "width": 250,
          "height": 219,
          "content": "Okay so this frame collects a variety of subframes that are the study of the dynamic graph node that we'll use and its many permutations, which denote whether that node represents a prompt added by the human user or a response added by the AI model. There are many dynamic states to the nodes, as you would know after helping me craft the system. There are some key actions that can be taken associated with a node, and those are:\nBeing able to branch from a single node\nMake clippings from the larger graph tree\nThose clippings would probably take place at the node level, where I'd be selecting the first and the last node, essentially identifying the area within the larger graph that I want to clip out. We've done a lot of work to iterate on the dynamic treatment of the node from a visual and UI standpoint. We know that there should be many different states associated with the node, which would denote different actions being taken place and system statuses associated with nodes or collections of nodes. This is a relatively robust study of different node behaviors and different orientations of the dynamic node. Ultimately what we are looking to do is finalize the design choices and the ultimate output for nodes and their many states. The hover state and the states that I have just described, which denote system statuses as the user engages more and more with the dynamic tree graph"
        },
        {
          "type": "note",
          "id": "dmUwH",
          "x": 1622,
          "y": 979,
          "width": 250,
          "height": 219,
          "content": "Again this is another study of the node and then it's dynamic visual treatment, which denotes different statuses of a given node. I think there are some explorations of using a crosshair motif to indicate that the node has been hovered over and is in a focused state. I'm not completely convinced that the crosshair is the right visual mechanic here but I do think that we're steering more closely to something that feels appropriate. We want to really be explicit that this node has been hovered over, is engaged with, and is in a focused state. I think a lot of the study here is valid. "
        },
        {
          "type": "note",
          "id": "ZJKHj",
          "x": 1298,
          "y": 152,
          "width": 250,
          "height": 219,
          "content": "Okay as I mentioned the nodes take on different geometric shapes based on their purpose and how they've been engaged with. We know that by standard the nodes are circular in orientation but then they can take on different geometric shapes to denote different actions that have been taken against them. This is a study of how to alter the orientation of the node to denote different actions that have been taken. "
        },
        {
          "type": "note",
          "id": "sRLMU",
          "x": 1457,
          "y": 7916,
          "width": 250,
          "height": 219,
          "content": "Okay this is the last frame that will pass over for the treatment of nodes visually and in their multi-state dynamicism. I thought this study did a particularly good job of articulating how the hover state might reveal a tool tip-esque card that at least gives me some truncated version of the output from the AI model or the prompt that was added. We do need to be cognizant of these cards not being able to probably house the entire output from either side of the equation. Therefore we need to elegantly solve for the character count limitation and also the way that the text would be truncated so it's visually appealing. It's giving enough context that's telling of the action that took place on that node but at the same time it's not overloading the user or the user's view and mis handling the text within the context of a card. "
        }
      ]
    },
