            {
              "type": "text",
              "id": "jwozu",
              "name": "State 2 Annotation",
              "fill": "#404040",
              "textGrowth": "fixed-width",
              "width": "fill_container",
              "content": "Canvas tools pill appears between input and model selector. Vertical divider separates tool groups. Model selector shifts right to accommodate.",
              "fontFamily": "Inconsolata",
              "fontSize": 9,
              "fontWeight": "normal",
              "letterSpacing": 0.3
            },
            {
              "type": "note",
              "id": "05FOH",
              "layoutPosition": "absolute",
              "x": 1315,
              "y": -143,
              "width": 250,
              "height": 219,
              "content": "Okay I really like these iterations of the bottom dock. I think they're super valid. The one issue that is glaring is the fact that you're using the peach or cream brand color that would only be used in a tertiary setting. I think that is the major glaring imperfection of these different treatments but I like this exploration generally. It does kind of reposition some of the global elements. For instance in earlier iterations we were positioning the model selector drop-down in the upper right-hand corner of the application and in this version we are establishing that it would live in the bottom right. I don't necessarily mind that but we have to have a perspective on the placement of global elements and have some rationale for why we're moving different global elements around. Obviously something like model selection would have to be very intentional in the way that we place it as the user would need to return to and engage with that menu again and again.\n\nI do think that there is a world where the actual denotation of the model and the opportunity to change models from, say, Claude to GPT4 etc. should have some mapping and be placed in closer proximity to the input field where you're engaging with the chat with the model. I think there's a lot that makes sense about the placement here so I think you can continue to explore this a bit but make sure that we bring it in line with the treatment visual and design treatment of the inner face components that we deem canonical. "
            }
          ]
        },
