                  "letterSpacing": 0.8
                },
                {
                  "type": "text",
                  "id": "JfE9M",
                  "name": "Content Body",
                  "fill": "#C8C8C8",
                  "textGrowth": "fixed-width",
                  "width": "fill_container",
                  "content": "Design systems are living organisms, not static deliverables. They evolve through usage patterns, team feedback, and technological shifts. The most effective systems establish a shared language between design and engineering — tokens for color, spacing, and typography that map directly to code variables.\n\nA node-based approach introduces spatial reasoning into the conversation. Each node becomes a discrete thought — branching, merging, and diverging the way real ideation works. Unlike linear chat, this preserves the topology of exploration: dead ends remain visible, breakthroughs connect back to their origins, and the full decision tree is navigable.\n\nThe critical insight is that conversation structure IS the artifact. The spatial layout encodes relationships that would be lost in a flat transcript.",
                  "lineHeight": 1.55,
                  "fontFamily": "Inter",
                  "fontSize": 13
                }
              ]
            },
