                {
                  "type": "text",
                  "id": "3bKVl",
                  "name": "m4text",
                  "fill": "#A8A8A8",
                  "textGrowth": "fixed-width",
                  "width": "fill_container",
                  "content": "A minimap would work if you keep the node count manageable per session. Beyond about fifty visible nodes, even the minimap becomes noise. Consider collapsible clusters — group related branches and let the user expand on demand.",
                  "lineHeight": 1.6,
                  "fontFamily": "Inconsolata",
                  "fontSize": 13
                }
              ]
            }
          ]
        },
        {
          "type": "note",
          "id": "hEj4v",
          "x": 1752,
          "y": 1978,
          "width": 250,
          "height": 333,
          "content": "Okay in terms of the timeline component, you absolutely smashed this. This feels very cool and brand appropriate. I really like the execution. I think the one piece to continue to explore around this execution is the different states that the timeline would take. I think we also have to think about how this is in its condensed version when it's not being engaged with because the component itself is quite substantial in size. We wouldn't always want to display it in the main view for the user as it would be cumbersome and distracting to other more important actions they take in a lot of the main states of the application. We need to solve for what the collapsed view is when the component is inactive and then I think we also need to consider how it transitions to the active state, which could look something like this. I'd also like to see additional enhancements to the treatment. Maybe we can come up with something even cooler that is reminiscent of what I'm looking at here but this is really sweet. Great job."
        },
        {
          "type": "note",
          "id": "Mtn2J",
          "x": 1727,
          "y": 4142,
          "width": 250,
          "height": 219,
          "content": "Okay this is a visual device that I think is very important to our system. When you engage with the clip tool, you're going to want to select a node as the beginning or the start of the clipping and then a node at the end, the tail end of the clipping. That is how you're specifying what subsection of the memory graph that you're clipping out.\n\nI think we really need to crack this now. I think what you're displaying is just that you're giving a unique selected state to the start node and you're giving a unique selected state to the end node. What we need to bear in mind is that this again is using the wrong brand colors and is not adhering to the rules we've established for the canonical versions of the components. Conceptually this is spot on but the execution is trash. We need to redo this. "
        },
        {
          "type": "note",
          "id": "i1wF3",
          "x": 1460,
          "y": 5095,
          "width": 250,
          "height": 219,
          "content": "Okay there's certainly a need for this type of motif or handling of key actions that would be mapped to the foundational or global layout for the application. I think there is some world where these types of components exist and are mapped to either the left edge of or right edge of the given layout, or are components that are sort of ancillary and are placed in a corner, whether it be the upper corner or lower corners of the layout. I think this kind of conceptually is valid but we need to make sure that we're not designing for things that don't actually exist within the system. I would just kind of air on the side of caution. There needs to be a very intentional reason as to why we're doing this but these elements feel kind of spot-on and what I'd expect to see within the system. "
        },
        {
          "type": "note",
          "id": "pPgIP",
          "x": 1562,
          "y": 9352,
          "width": 250,
          "height": 219,
          "content": "Okay this is really cool. I think it feels very akin to the way that we're treating the Toast messaging, which we had sort of envisioned to be mapped to the bottom most of the layout and only appear as text that animates out after a finite period of time.\n\nI think the issue with treating the text input as if it were part of the computer terminal is just that we're not making it feel like a really special experience and engaging with the input field is kind of part of the core of what makes this experience interesting. I think this might be the wrong solution but I can see there potentially being a world where this does exist within the system and some other permutation. I think the pattern is strong. It looks really good and it's on brand but I don't think we got all the way there from a functionality/mechanical standpoint. We're really not saying the right thing because we're not making the input field feel like a sort of jewel or something that's special to the system. "
        }
      ]
    },
